Description: Connecting students to freelance jobs.
Headquarters Regions: Greater Los Angeles Area, West Coast, Western US
Full Description: [StudentFreelance.com](http://www.studentfreelance.com) keeps jobs in America by insourcing work to students. Before [StudentFreelance.com](http://www.studentfreelance.com) students only had two options. They could take up an internship, which meant a lot of boring busywork, being underappreciated and underpaid (if paid at all), and walking away without gaining the experience desired. Their only other option was to take a minimum wage job that would not help them achieve their career goals. Employers also had their share of problems before [StudentFreelance.com](http://www.studentfreelance.com). They could spend a ton of money competing over local professionals with larger sized companies that have much bigger pockets, or they could outsource their work to foreign countries where there are language barriers, different time zones, cultural differences, and the quality of work would suffer as a result. [StudentFreelance.com](http://www.studentfreelance.com) directly addresses these problems and solves them by introducing employers to students studying in American schools. With [StudentFreelance.com](http://www.studentfreelance.com), students can set their work hours, gain relevant experience, and earn an income. Employers gain access to a talented workforce that is cost effective and efficient to scale.

Description: Kewl Circle is a location-based, interest centric social media app helping users be social online and offline
Headquarters Regions: Greater New York Area, East Coast, Northeastern US
Full Description: In recent years, a new trend has occurred where people are immensely “social” online via various social media applications, but minimally social in real life. Millions of people around the world open up social media apps on their Smartphones every single day before they even get out of bed, yet isolate themselves in real life and shut the metaphoric door on meeting new people, doing fun activities and creating real social experiences. It’s not just one social media app-the majority of social media apps have created this dichotomy. People pretend not to notice the social isolation existing in today’s world, but our team of developers, designers, marketers and business professionals have not only recognized the issue and experienced it first-hand, we created an app that will hopefully reverse the new “social norm" before it’s too late. This is how Kewl Circle was conceptualized and brought to life in November of 2014. Our vision for the Kewl Circle app is to serve as a global social media platform that brings life back to socialization and makes social media social again.

Description: Clockety is the world's first smartphone projection clock.
Headquarters Regions: San Francisco Bay Area, West Coast, Western US
Full Description: Clockety is the world's first smartphone projection clock. Unlike typical projection clocks that are bulky and travel un-friendly, Clockety is small and portable, so you can keep it on your nightstand or take it with you when you’re on-the-go. Slip it into your bag or purse to use in your hotel room. Clockety is smart, customizable, and easy to use. It attaches to the back of your phone and the complimentary iPhone app offers customized control options. You can tap on the phone to turn Clockety on/off at night or turn it on using an Alarm. Clockety is hassle-free! It’s powered by a small watch battery that lasts for over a year, so you don’t have to worry about plugging into a wall outlet to charge. Clockety doesn’t require bluetooth or Wi-Fi, so you don’t have to worry about pairing, Wi-Fi connectivity or USB cables. Simply snap Clockety on the back of your phone, fire up the app, get some sleep! Clockety's different components were carefully selected after trying out various specifications and variations. After exploring several types of lenses that varied in diameter and focal length, we selected Clockety’s lens. We spent a great deal of time on this aspect of the project because we wanted to make sure that Clockety would be able to clearly project the time on all standard ceiling heights. We also calculated the distance between different nightstands and ceilings to make sure that Clockety could clearly project the time for almost all of the combinations.
